  "local_port": 43390,
  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What is the proof for triangular law of vectors?",
  "response": "The triangular law of vectors states that if two vectors are represented by two sides of a triangle taken in order, then their resultant is given by the third side of the triangle taken in the opposite order. Let's go through the proof of this law step by step.\n\n### Proof of the Triangular Law of Vectors\n\nConsider two vectors \\(\\vec{A}\\) and \\(\\vec{B}\\) represented by the sides of a triangle in such a way that the tail of \\(\\vec{B}\\) coincides with the head of \\(\\vec{A}\\).\n\n1. **Representation of Vectors**:\n   - Let \\(\\vec{A}\\) be represented by the line segment \\(\\overrightarrow{OA}\\).\n   - Let \\(\\vec{B}\\) be represented by the line segment \\(\\overrightarrow{AB}\\), such that point \\(A\\) is the head of \\(\\vec{A}\\) and the tail of \\(\\vec{B}\\).\n\n2. **Resultant Vector**:\n   - The resultant vector \\(\\vec{R}\\) of \\(\\vec{A}\\) and \\(\\vec{B}\\) can be represented by the line segment \\(\\overrightarrow{OB}\\), where \\(O\\) is the tail of \\(\\vec{A}\\) and \\(B\\) is the head of \\(\\vec{B}\\).\n\n3. **Using the Parallelogram Law**:\n   - According to the parallelogram law of vector addition, if \\(\\vec{A}\\) and \\(\\vec{B}\\) are represented by the sides of a parallelogram, then the resultant vector \\(\\vec{R}\\) is represented by the diagonal of the parallelogram drawn from the same point.\n\n4. **Constructing the Parallelogram**:\n   - Draw a line segment \\(\\overrightarrow{OC}\\) parallel to \\(\\overrightarrow{AB}\\) and equal in length to \\(\\overrightarrow{AB}\\), such that \\(C\\) is the head of \\(\\vec{B}\\) when \\(\\vec{B}\\) is moved to start from \\(O\\).\n   - Now, \\(\\overrightarrow{OA}\\) and \\(\\overrightarrow{OC}\\) form the sides of a parallelogram \\(OACB\\).\n\n5. **Resultant from Parallelogram**:\n   - The diagonal \\(\\overrightarrow{OC}\\) of the parallelogram \\(OACB\\) represents the resultant vector \\(\\vec{R}\\) of \\(\\vec{A}\\) and \\(\\vec{B}\\).\n\n6. **Relating to the Triangle**:\n   - Notice that \\(\\overrightarrow{OC}\\) is also the same as \\(\\overrightarrow{OB}\\) because \\(C\\) coincides with \\(B\\) in the triangle construction.\n   - Therefore, \\(\\overrightarrow{OB}\\) represents the resultant vector \\(\\vec{R}\\).\n\n7. **Conclusion**:\n   - Hence, the resultant vector \\(\\vec{R}\\) of \\(\\vec{A}\\) and \\(\\vec{B}\\) is given by the third side of the triangle \\(\\overrightarrow{OB}\\) taken in the opposite order.\n\nThus, we have shown that the resultant of two vectors \\(\\vec{A}\\) and \\(\\vec{B}\\) can be obtained by using the triangular law, where \\(\\vec{R} = \\vec{A} + \\vec{B}\\) is represented by the third side of the triangle taken in the opposite order.\n\nThis completes the proof of the triangular law of vectors.",
